elements.content: The reaction of 3-(N1-uracyl)­propanoic acid (LH) with (t-Bu2SnO)3 in a 3:1 ratio afforded the hydroxide-bridged dimer [t-Bu2Sn­(μ-OH)­L]2 (1). A similar reaction involving bis­(tri-n-butyltin)­oxide, (n-Bu3Sn)2O, in a 2:1 ratio afforded the one-dimensional (1D) coordination polymer [(n-Bu3SnL)] n (2). Similarly, the reaction of LH with (MeOAr)2­TeO in a 2:1 ratio afforded the mononuclear [(MeOAr)2­TeL2]·​H2O (3). On the other hand, a similar reaction in a 1:1 ratio gave the dinuclear product [{(MeOAr)2­TeL}2O]·​C2H5OH·​CH3OH·​H2O (4). The reaction of complex 1 with CuCl2 in a 1:1 ratio yielded [Cu­(II)­L2H2O]2·​6H2O (5). All the complexes show an extensive supramolecular organization in the solid state as a result of several intermolecular interactions. The role of uracil substituents in determining the final course of the supramolecular assembly is discussed. A tetrameric uracil supramolecular motif is formed in the crystal structure of complex 1 as a result of C–H···O interactions. Uracil–water interactions involving only C–H···O interactions have been observed in complex 5.

elements.content: The rational design and synthesis of novel supramolecular architectures are of current interest in the field of crystal engineering. The involvement of nucleobases in strong hydrogen bonds and resulting in supramolecular architectures is well-known, the most well-known and illustrated example being the structure of DNA. In recent years, specific interactions that are likely to occur between nucleobases and the consequent structure directing capability that such an interaction is likely to lead, has triggered the anchoring of nucleobases on a variety of functional molecules including carbon nanotubes. We have been working in the area of main-group organometallic chemistry for some time and have extensively explored the reactions of organotin oxides, organotin hydroxides, and oxide-hydroxides with protic acids. A similar exercise, but to a limited extent, has also been carried out by us on organotelluroxanes. These studies revealed to us that, apart from the structural diversity of the products, the resulting supramolecular interactions are very rich and fraught with interesting possibilities. Thus, among the novel supramolecular architectures realized in these systems, the Rangoli pattern in the hexa-ferrocenyl derivative [n-BuSn­(O)­(O2CCH2C5H4­FeC5H5)]6 and an extended capsule-like 3D network in the trinuclear macrocycle [n-Bu2Sn­{2,5­(C5H3N)-(COO)2­(H2O)}]3 are aesthetically pleasing. In an earlier study, we reported some unique supramolecular motifs including an unprecedented homotrimeric base pairing of adenine on an organostannoxane platform. Additionally, we have also been able to realize unprecedented uracil–water interaction that involves only C–H···O bonds.

Introduction

The rational design and synthesis of novel supramolecular architectures are of current interest in the field of crystal engineering. The involvement of nucleobases in strong hydrogen bonds and resulting in supramolecular architectures is well-known, the most well-known and illustrated example being the structure of DNA. In recent years, specific interactions that are likely to occur between nucleobases and the consequent structure directing capability that such an interaction is likely to lead, has triggered the anchoring of nucleobases on a variety of functional molecules including carbon nanotubes. We have been working in the area of main-group organometallic chemistry for some time and have extensively explored the reactions of organotin oxides, organotin hydroxides, and oxide-hydroxides with protic acids. A similar exercise, but to a limited extent, has also been carried out by us on organotelluroxanes. These studies revealed to us that, apart from the structural diversity of the products, the resulting supramolecular interactions are very rich and fraught with interesting possibilities. Thus, among the novel supramolecular architectures realized in these systems, the Rangoli pattern in the hexa-ferrocenyl derivative [n-BuSn(O)(O2CCH2C5H4FeC5H5)]6  and an extended capsule-like 3D network in the trinuclear macrocycle [n-Bu2Sn{2,5(C5H3N)-(COO)2(H2O)}]3  are aesthetically pleasing. Recently, we were interested in studying if such an approach can also be extended to nucleobases. Our intention was in capturing rare or unique supramolecular motifs of nucleobases. In an earlier study, we reported some unique supramolecular motifs including an unprecedented homotrimeric base pairing of adenine on an organostannoxane platform. In view of the paucity of studies involving uracil, we chose to prepare multi-uracil arrays using organostannoxane and organotelluroxane platforms and study the supramolecular motifs in such systems. In this article, we report the synthesis and structural characterization of [t-Bu2Sn(μ-OH)L]2 (1), [(n-Bu3SnL)] n  (2), [(MeOAr)2TeL2]⋅H2O (3), [{(MeOAr)2TeL}2O]⋅C2H5OH⋅CH3OH⋅H2O (4), and [Cu(II)L2H2O]2⋅6H2O (5) [LH = 3-(N1-uracyl)propanoic acid]. As discussed below, we have captured new supramolecular structural motifs involving homouracil C-H⋅⋅⋅O interactions. Additionally, we have also been able to realize unprecedented uracil-water interaction that involves only C-H⋅⋅⋅O bonds.

Experimental Section

Reagents and General Procedure

All the reactions were performed under a dry nitrogen atmosphere by employing standard Schlenk techniques. Solvents were stored over appropriate reagents and distilled under nitrogen prior to use. [(n-Bu3Sn)2O] and CuCl2⋅2H2O were purchased from Aldrich and used as supplied. [t-Bu2SnO]3, (MeOAr)2TeO,and LH were prepared according to literature procedures.

elements.content: 1H and 119Sn NMR spectra were recorded on a JEOL JNM Lambda spectrometer operating at 500.0 and 150.0 MHz, respectively. The chemical shifts are referenced with respect to tetramethylsilane (for 1H) and tetramethyltin (for 119Sn). IR spectra were recorded as KBr pellets on a Bruker Vector22 FT IR spectrophotometer operating from 400 to 4000 cm–1. High-resolution ESI-MS spectra were recorded on a MICROMASS QUATTRO II triple quadrupole mass spectrometer. Methanol/DMSO was used as the solvent for the ESI-MS studies. Elemental analyses were carried out using a thermoquest CE instruments model EA/110 CHNS-O elemental analyzer. Melting points were recorded using a JSGW melting point apparatus and are uncorrected. Suitable crystals for single-crystal X-ray diffraction measurements were mounted on a Bruker D8 QUEST diffractometer. Data were collected at 100(2) K using graphite monochromated Mo Kα radiation [λα = 0. 71069 Å]. The structures were solved by direct methods and refined (SHELXL 97) by full-matrix least-squares procedures on F 2. The hydrogen atoms were included in idealized positions and were refined according to the riding model. Non-hydrogen atoms were refined with anisotropic displacement parameters. The O–H protons were included from the electron density map and refined isotropically. Details of the data collection and refinement parameters of compounds (1–5) are given in Table . The crystallographic figures have been generated using Diamond 3.2 g. Powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) patterns were recorded with a Bruker D8 advance diffractometer equipped with nickel-filtered Cu Kα radiation. Powder X-ray diffraction (PXRD) patterns of complexes 1–5 were in close agreement with the simulated patterns (Figures S13–S17, ). The differences in intensity could be due to the preferred orientation in the powder samples.

elements.content: The reactions of organotin/organotellurium oxides with carboxylic acids have been explored very well. In general, the reactions of organotin oxides-hydroxides and oxide-hydroxides with carboxylic acids are known to afford a wide range of products whose structure is dependent on the number of organic substituents on tin. Several hydrogen bonding interactions are present in the crystal structure of complex 1. The bridging hydroxide ligands are involved in an intramolecular hydrogen bonding with the CO unit of the carboxylate ligands (Figure ). Imine hydrogen (H3N) and O4 oxygen of the uracil moiety interact with the CO unit (O3) and H7B of the carboxylate, respectively, by a pair of intermolecular hydrogen bonding to form a 2D supramolecular structure (Figure ). Such 2D frameworks interact by three sets of hydrogen bonding (C5–H5···O2, C6–H6···O4, and C8–H8A···O4) to form a 3D framework (Figure a). Within this 3D framework is present a novel 2D supramolecular grid involving a homouracil array. In the latter, each uracil unit interacts with four nearest uracil bases by intermolecular C–H···O hydrogen bonding [distances (Å): H6···O4, 2.764(4); H5···O2, 2.651(4); Angles (deg): ∠C6–H6···O4, 153.30(2); ∠C5–H5···O2, 173.68(2)] to generate an 18-membered macrocycle; hydrogen bonding interactions among the latter generates the 2D supramolecular grid (Figure b,c). Interestingly, within the tetrameric array, the uracil units are placed nearly equidistant from each other (av. ∼6.8 Å). To the best of our knowledge, such tetrameric uracil structural motifs are unknown hitherto (Figure c).

elements.content: Complex 2 consists of a 1D polymeric chain as a result of monodentate carboxylate and uracil oxygen atom coordination to the tin atom (Figure ). Normally, triorganotin carboxylates are coordination polymers in their solid state where the carboxylate ligand is involved in bridging successive triorganotin units (Chart ). Polymeric structures, such as what is found in complex 2, involving two different coordinating centers at the tin, though not common, are found in the literature (Chart ). Although the asymmetric unit consists of two crystallographically unique polymeric building units, the coordination mode of tin ions (Sn1 and Sn1A) are almost similar. Selected bond parameters are summarized in the caption of Figure . Each tin is five-coordinate in a distorted trigonal-bipyramidal geometry (τ = 0.732) with the oxygen atoms occupying the axial positions (, Figure S4). The carboxylate and the uracil oxygen atom bind to tin in an analogous manner to what was observed for [{Sn­(C4H9)3­(uracil-1-acetate)} n ].

elements.content: The supramolecular structure of compound 3 reveals interesting uracil–water hydrogen bonding interactions. Studying the interactions between water and nucleobases in microsolvation conditions is important because it allows an understanding of the effects of hydration on the DNA structure. Being the simplest molecular models of the interactions between the biologically important nitrogen bases and water, many theoretical studies have been done on the uracil–water system. In the current instance, we note that the uracil moieties of complex 3 interact with only one hydrogen of water through O4/O4A oxygen (O9–H9A···O4 and O9–H9B···O4A) (Figure ). Although this hydrogen bonding motif is not among the most favorable geometries, it is one of the possible geometries reported by Bao et al. The optimized most-favorable geometries of the mono-water–uracil system are given in Chart , where the oxygen atom of water also participates in hydrogen bonding along with one of its hydrogens.

elements.content: In conclusion, we have utilized organostannoxane and organotellurium platforms to build multi-uracil arrays with an intention to study the hydrogen bonding interactions involving the nucleobase. The supramolecular chemistry of such systems has been shown to be extremely rich, containing diverse noncovalent interactions, the most prominent of these being the interactions between the nucleobases themselves. We have observed for the first time a tetrameric uracil supramolecular motif formed as a result of C–H···O interactions. Also, we have observed uracil–water interactions involving C–H···O interactions that also are unprecedented. These studies point out the importance of weak hydrogen bonds in directing supramolecular structures involving nucleobases, and it is likely that such interactions are prevalent in biologically relevant molecules possessing perhaps not only a structural role but also a functional role.
